Olaide Oyelude, Katsina A middle-aged man, Abdulrazaq Ibrahim, has been remanded in a Katsina correction facility over alleged criminal conspiracy and armed robbery. The defendant was remanded by the presiding magistrate of a Katsina Senior Magistrateâ€™s Court, Hajiya Fadile Dikko. The case was adjourned till January 16, 2020. Earlier, the police said Ibrahim, along with a yet-to-be identified man, attacked and robbed a commercial motorcyclist, Ibrahim Abdulkarim, of his unregistered Daylong motorcycle, valued at N175,000. According to the police, Ibrahim and his accomplice had on October 29, 2019 engaged the services of Abdulkarim to carry them to Unguwar Daudu village, in Niger Republic, at an agreed sum of N200. The police explained that during the trip, the two men directed their victim to stop to enable them to pick a mat which fell off. As soon as he stopped, they attacked him with a machete, inflicting several injuries on him in the process. They left him for dead and allegedly made away with the motorcycle. The court further heard that nemesis caught up with the defendant a few days after the attack when Abdulkarim spotted him at Garki village and raised the alarm. Passersby responded by arresting Ibrahim, who they handed over to the police. Ibrahim was subsequently charged with armed robbery under sections 6(b) and 1(2)(a)(b) of the Robbery and Firearms Special Provision Act, Cap. RII, LFN, 2004. The police prosecutor, Sergeant Bello Lawal, prayed the court to grant the police additional time to conclude their investigations. The court granted his prayers and subsequently adjourned the matter. Copyright PUNCH. All rights reserved. This material, and other digital content on this website, may not be reproduced, published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed in whole or in part without prior express written permission from PUNCH. Contact: theeditor@punchng.com   